[sleep: 3s]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Create a new list called "Help Desk Inbox" with these columns: Request (single line text), Submitted By (person), Details (multiple lines of text), Category (single line text), Priority (single line text), AI Summary (multiple lines of text).]

[wait]

[sleep: 5s]

[navigate: ${LIST}]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Add exactly these 8 rows — leave Category, Priority, and AI Summary blank on every row: 1. Request: "cant login" | Submitted By: me | Details: "i cant log into my computer at all. i have a client presentation in 2 hours and need access urgently. tried restarting 3 times." 2. Request: "wifi sucks in bldg 3" | Submitted By: me | Details: "the wifi in building 3 has been terrible for a week. drops every 20 min. affects me and at least 4 others on my team." 3. Request: "printer jammed" | Submitted By: me | Details: "the printer on floor 2 is jammed again. tried clearing it but no luck. not urgent." 4. Request: "need access to shared drive" | Submitted By: me | Details: "i need access to the Q4 marketing shared drive for the campaign launch next week." 5. Request: "vpn keeps dropping" | Submitted By: me | Details: "vpn disconnects every hour or so when working remote. started happening 3 days ago. network team looked at it but no fix yet." 6. Request: "new hire laptop setup" | Submitted By: me | Details: "we have a new hire starting monday. need laptop provisioned with standard software and vpn access." 7. Request: "email not syncing" | Submitted By: me | Details: "outlook on my phone stopped syncing 2 days ago. getting emails on desktop but not mobile." 8. Request: "projector in conf room b broken" | Submitted By: me | Details: "projector in conference room B wont turn on. we have a board meeting tomorrow morning."]

[wait]

[new-chat]

Confirm 8 items are visible with Request, Submitted By, and Details populated,
and Category, Priority, and AI Summary columns are all empty.

[pause]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${LIST}]

This is what an unmanaged intake queue looks like. Free-text requests, no
categorization, no way to prioritize. Someone wrote "cant login" and someone
else wrote "wifi sucks in bldg 3." How does a support lead triage this?
Usually they read every single ticket. Let's try something faster.

[pause]

[open-chat]

[prompt: Read every item in this list. For each row, fill in the Category column based on what the request is about, set the Priority based on urgency and business impact, and write a one-sentence AI Summary.]

[wait]

Watch the columns fill in. Copilot read the details of every request and
made judgment calls. Notice that "cant login" got Critical priority because
the details mention a client presentation today. "wifi sucks in bldg 3" got
High because it's affecting multiple people for a week. The printer issue
is Low. These aren't random — they're based on the actual business impact
described in the Details column.

[pause]

Now filter by Priority equals Critical. One result — Jordan's locked account.
Your team knows exactly what to tackle first.

[pause: Show the Critical filter — one result]

Let's go deeper. Can the AI spot patterns across tickets?

[prompt: Which requests are likely related to the same root cause?]

[wait]

Copilot connected the VPN disconnects and the wifi drops — both are network
issues, both started recently. It's not just sorting tickets — it's spotting
patterns that a human triaging one ticket at a time would miss.

[pause]

